# Wulfharth, King of Storms

**Wulfharth** — known also as **Ysmir**, the **Ash-King**, and the **Breath of Kyne** — is one of the most enigmatic and consequential figures in the history of Tamriel. High King of **Skyrim** in the First Era, he died and was resurrected at least three times, participated in the **Battle of Red Mountain**, and played a crucial role in the ascension of **Tiber Septim** to godhood. His legend is inseparable from the mystery of **Talos**.

## The Five Songs of Wulfharth

Wulfharth's history is transmitted through the **Five Songs of King Wulfharth**, an ancient Nordic text that weaves together history and myth in an inextricable way.

### First Song — The Ascension

Wulfharth became High King of Skyrim during the First Era, elected by the **Moot** (the assembly of Jarls). He was a powerful **Tongue** — a master of the **Thu'um** whose voice could command storms. Under his reign, he restored the cult of **Shor** (the Nordic aspect of Lorkhan) and expelled the priests of the Imperial Divines.

### Second Song — Death at Red Mountain

Wulfharth led Nordic armies to **Red Mountain** to aid the Dwemer against the Chimer (or the Chimer against the Dwemer — the sources contradict each other). He was slain there — disintegrated by a Shout so powerful that only ashes remained. Hence his title: the **Ash-King**.

### Third Song — Resurrection by Kyne

**Kyne**, goddess of storms and patroness of the Nords, called Wulfharth back from the dead. Her divine breath reconstituted the king from his ashes. Wulfharth became the **Breath of Kyne** — neither living nor dead, a storm spirit incarnated in flesh.

### Fourth Song — The Second Death

Wulfharth died again during a conflict with the Orcs, then was resurrected once more. Each death and resurrection seemed to draw him closer to the divine nature of Shor/Lorkhan — as if dying and being reborn was his *mode of existence*.

### Fifth Song — Talos

The Fifth Song is the most controversial: it connects Wulfharth to the ascension of Tiber Septim.

## The Enantiomorph of Talos

### The Mystery

The greatest mystery surrounding Wulfharth is his role in the creation of **Talos**. According to the **Arcturian Heresy** and other esoteric sources, Talos is not a single individual who became a god — he is a fusion of **three persons** forming an **Enantiomorph**:

<CausalChain items={[
  { text: "Hjalti Early-Beard (the Warrior) — the future 'Tiber Septim'" },
  { text: "Wulfharth Ash-King (the King) — the Breath of Kyne" },
  { text: "Zurin Arctus (the Mage) — the Imperial War Wizard" },
  { text: "= TALOS, the Ninth Divine (fusion of the three)", indent: 1 }
]} />

### The Roles

Within the Enantiomorph:
- **Hjalti** is the "Rebel" — the one who acts and conquers
- **Wulfharth** is the "King" — the one who holds divine legitimacy (as a Shezarrine, avatar of Shor)
- **Zurin Arctus** is the "Observer" — the one who is betrayed and whose sacrifice catalyzes the fusion

### The Betrayal

According to the Arcturian Heresy, Hjalti/Tiber Septim betrayed Wulfharth by absorbing his vital essence to power the **Numidium** — the divine Dwemer golem he used to conquer Tamriel. Wulfharth, betrayed, involuntarily merged with the other two to form the divine entity Talos. Zurin Arctus, also betrayed, became the **Mantella** — the soul gem powering the Numidium.

## The Nature of Wulfharth

### Shezarrine

Wulfharth is identified as a **Shezarrine** — a mortal avatar of **Shor/Lorkhan**. Like Lorkhan, he dies and is reborn, is betrayed and sacrifices himself. This nature explains:
- His multiple resurrections (Lorkhan is the god who dies and returns)
- His association with storms (Shor is a god of wind and war)
- His participation in the Enantiomorph (he replays the cosmic role of Lorkhan)

### The Title of Ysmir

**Ysmir** ("Dragon of the North") is a title borne by Wulfharth, but also by Tiber Septim and the Dovahkiin of the Fourth Era. This title seems to mark those who embody the "archetypal Nordic hero" — a mortal so powerful that they touch the divine. The Greybeards bestow this title upon the rare individuals they recognize as worthy.

## Legacy

Wulfharth is living (and dead, and re-living) proof that in the Elder Scrolls universe, individual identity is more fluid than mortal logic would suppose. He is simultaneously a historical king, a storm spirit, an aspect of Lorkhan, and a third of a god. His legend illustrates the fundamental principle of Tamrielic metaphysics: the boundary between mortal and divine is not a wall, but a threshold that some cross — sometimes without meaning to.
